If that fight happens, McGregor is getting knocked out.

[Predictions]

@B7L7  how is Charles Oliveira (a grappler and all-time submission wins leader) a better stylistic matchup for Connor McGregor then Max Holloway is? Max Holloway has probably never attempted a take down in his UFC career and is going to stay on the feet with Conor McGregor and box with him. Holloway is no doubt the better boxer but he doesn’t have the power to knock McGregor out, so McGregor has a punchers chance to catch Holloway with something and win the fight, but Holloway probably wins by decision… whereas Charles Oliveira knows McGregor can’t stop the takedown and he can out grapple McGregor in his sleep so he will do the same thing he did with Max…. Pursue the takedown ASAP and look to submit Conor which he probably will because Max is way harder to finish on the ground then Conor is, at least historically…

The fact that you posted that tells me you know absolutely nothing about fighting or what a matchup actually is lol also, the UFC probably doesn’t want to put McGregor in a fight where he’s just going to get taken to the ground and submitted for his comeback fight. They want Connor to have a good showing because at the end of the day they want to keep him fighting because he is their biggest draw and has the most earning potential so they give him a fight where they know he’s going to stay on his feet, which is a fight with Max Holloway

[Predictions]

@Gilpin Conor was probably the best counter striker we've ever seen, hence why he reached the heights he did. But i think his style is pretty much figured out. I mean he  lost against a Nate Diaz (In His Prime mind you) who he was supposed walk through and stop. Fought a prime Khabib and was smoked but no shame there. Fought a Prime Porrier and was TKO'd. (I'm only counting their second fight btw). I think Ferguson decimates him, barboza was a tough out. People scroll on tik tok and see an edit of him knocking out Aldo and tko'ing Marcus Brimage and say with a straight face he is the greatest fw or lw ever. The guy was amazing and had exceptional talent, but any time the fight was taken to HIM, he looked for a way out. Im not saying he wouldnt crack max a few times and hurt him, but I'd be shocked to see conor any higher than +200

* Edited at 04.28.2026,  7:39 PM ET *

[Predictions]

@Gilpin the skill doesn't leave you, but when you're physically washed you can't show what you got. I can use this example on myself since I played pro football/soccer before I started training MMA and was technically a very good player. But, when I stopped training for an extended period of time and I tried to come back at semi pro level, I couldn't showcase my technical skill in a match because I just didn't have the energy and strength to do it consistently. When you're tired and weak your body behaves differently. Now imagine a 38 year old Conor McGregor, who's not a footballer but a CONTACT combat sport athlete, meaning he's absorbed a lot of damage throughout his career. As I already said, since 2021 you can probably count on one hand the number of times he had tough training sessions. I agree the skill doesn't leave you, but you are unable to show it when you don't have the physicals to match it.

